{"title_page": "Fran G\u00e1mez", "text_new": "{{Spanish name|G\u00e1mez|L\u00f3pez}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Fran G\u00e1mez\n| image = \n| full_name = Francisco G\u00e1mez L\u00f3pez\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1991|7|27|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Sagunto]], Spain\n| height = 1.74 m\n| position = [[Defender (association football)#Full-back|Right back]]\n| currentclub = [[RCD Mallorca|Mallorca]]\n| clubnumber = 15\n| youthyears1 = 2009\u20132010 | youthclubs1 = [[CD Acero|Acero]]\n| years1 = 2010\u20132013 | clubs1 = [[CD Acero|Acero]] | caps1 = ? | goals1 = 6\n| years2 = 2013\u20132018 | clubs2 = [[Atl\u00e9tico Saguntino|Saguntino]] | caps2 = 161 | goals2 = 21\n| years3 = 2018\u2013 | clubs3 = [[RCD Mallorca|Mallorca]] | caps3 = 33 | goals3 = 2\n| nationalyears1 = | nationalteam1 = | nationalcaps1 = | nationalgoals1 = \n| club-update = 9 June 2019\n| nationalteam-update = \n}}\n\n'''Francisco''' \"'''Fran'''\" '''G\u00e1mez L\u00f3pez''' (born 27 July 1991) is a Spanish [[Association football|footballer]] who plays for [[RCD Mallorca]]. Mainly a [[Defender (association football)#Full-back|right back]], he can also play as a [[Midfielder#Winger|right winger]].\n\n==Club career==\nBorn in [[Sagunto]], [[Valencian Community]], G\u00e1mez was a [[CD Acero]] youth graduate. He made his first team debut in the 2010\u201311 season, in the regional leagues.\n\nOn 16 June 2013, G\u00e1mez signed for [[Tercera Divisi\u00f3n]] side [[Atl\u00e9tico Saguntino]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.atleticosaguntino.es/Actualidad/Noticia/ver,14/|title=Fran G\u00e1mez firma por el Saguntino|trans-title=Fran G\u00e1mez signs for Saguntino|publisher=Atl\u00e9tico Saguntino|language=es|date=16 June 2013|access-date=9 June 2018}}</ref> An undisputed starter, he scored a career-best 11 goals during the [[2015\u201316 Tercera Divisi\u00f3n|2015\u201316 season]], achieving promotion to [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B]]; he also acted as [[Captain (association football)|team captain]] during the most of his spell.\n\nOn 30 January 2018, G\u00e1mez signed a two-and-a-half-year deal with [[RCD Mallorca]] also in the third division,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rcdmallorca.es/contenidos/noticias/noticia/fran-gamez-es-nuevo-jugador-del-rcd-mallorca|title=Fran G\u00e1mez es nuevo jugador del RCD Mallorca|trans-title=Fran G\u00e1mez is the new player of RCD Mallorca|publisher=RCD Mallorca|language=es|date=30 January 2018|access-date=9 June 2018}}</ref> after the club activated his [[Euro|\u20ac]] 30,000 buyout clause.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elmundo.es/baleares/2018/01/30/5a70480646163f5e7c8b45a4.html|title=Fran G\u00e1mez, fichaje sorpresa|trans-title=Fran G\u00e1mez, surprise signing|publisher=[[El Mundo (Spain)|El Mundo]]|language=es|date=30 January 2018|access-date=9 June 2018}}</ref> He contributed with one goal in seven appearances, as his side [[2017\u201318 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|achieved promotion]] to [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]] after a one-year absence.\n\nG\u00e1mez made his professional debut on 19 August 2018, starting in a 1\u20130 home win against [[CA Osasuna]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marca.com/futbol/segunda-division/2018/08/19/5b799fd8468aeb57088b45cf.html|title=Abd\u00f3n Prats gu\u00eda a un Mallorca que convence en su vuelta a Segunda|trans-title=Abd\u00f3n Prats leads a Mallorca which convince in their return to ''Segunda''|publisher=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]]|language=es|date=19 August 2018|access-date=19 August 2018}}</ref> He scored his first professional goal on 29 September, in a 1\u20131 away draw against [[CD Lugo]], and finished [[2018\u201319 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|the campaign]] as a starter as the club reached another promotion.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{BDFutbol|23342}}\n*{{LaPreferente|87188<!-- /gamez -->}}\n*{{Soccerway|francisco-gamez-lopez/456121}}\n\n{{RCD Mallorca squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gamez, Fran}}\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Sagunto]]\n[[Category:Spanish footballers]]\n[[Category:Valencian footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B players]]\n[[Category:Tercera Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Divisiones Regionales de F\u00fatbol players]]\n[[Category:Atl\u00e9tico Saguntino players]]\n[[Category:RCD Mallorca players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Spanish name|G\u00e1mez|L\u00f3pez}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Fran G\u00e1mez\n| image =\n| fullname = Francisco G\u00e1mez L\u00f3pez\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1991|7|27|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Sagunto]], Spain\n| height = 1.74 m\n| position = [[Defender (association football)#Full-back|Right back]]\n| currentclub = [[RCD Mallorca|Mallorca]]\n| clubnumber = 15\n| youthyears1 = 2009\u20132010 | youthclubs1 = [[CD Acero|Acero]]\n| years1 = 2010\u20132013 | clubs1 = [[CD Acero|Acero]] | caps1 = ? | goals1 = 6\n| years2 = 2013\u20132018 | clubs2 = [[Atl\u00e9tico Saguntino|Saguntino]] | caps2 = 161 | goals2 = 21\n| years3 = 2018\u2013 | clubs3 = [[RCD Mallorca|Mallorca]] | caps3 = 33 | goals3 = 2\n| nationalyears1 = | nationalteam1 = | nationalcaps1 = | nationalgoals1 = \n| club-update = 9 June 2019\n| nationalteam-update = \n}}\n'''Francisco''' \"'''Fran'''\" '''G\u00e1mez L\u00f3pez''' (born 27 July 1991) is a Spanish [[Association football|footballer]] who plays for [[RCD Mallorca]]. Mainly a [[Defender (association football)#Full-back|right back]], he can also play as a [[Midfielder#Winger|right winger]].\n\n==Club career==\nBorn in [[Sagunto]], [[Valencian Community]], G\u00e1mez was a [[CD Acero]] youth graduate. He made his first team debut in the 2010\u201311 season, in the regional leagues.\n\nOn 16 June 2013, G\u00e1mez signed for [[Tercera Divisi\u00f3n]] side [[Atl\u00e9tico Saguntino]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.atleticosaguntino.es/Actualidad/Noticia/ver,14/|title=Fran G\u00e1mez firma por el Saguntino|trans-title=Fran G\u00e1mez signs for Saguntino|publisher=Atl\u00e9tico Saguntino|language=es|date=16 June 2013|access-date=9 June 2018}}</ref> An undisputed starter, he scored a career-best 11 goals during the [[2015\u201316 Tercera Divisi\u00f3n|2015\u201316 season]], achieving promotion to [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B]]; he also acted as [[Captain (association football)|team captain]] during the most of his spell.\n\nOn 30 January 2018, G\u00e1mez signed a two-and-a-half-year deal with [[RCD Mallorca]] also in the third division,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rcdmallorca.es/contenidos/noticias/noticia/fran-gamez-es-nuevo-jugador-del-rcd-mallorca|title=Fran G\u00e1mez es nuevo jugador del RCD Mallorca|trans-title=Fran G\u00e1mez is the new player of RCD Mallorca|publisher=RCD Mallorca|language=es|date=30 January 2018|access-date=9 June 2018}}</ref> after the club activated his [[Euro|\u20ac]] 30,000 buyout clause.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elmundo.es/baleares/2018/01/30/5a70480646163f5e7c8b45a4.html|title=Fran G\u00e1mez, fichaje sorpresa|trans-title=Fran G\u00e1mez, surprise signing|publisher=[[El Mundo (Spain)|El Mundo]]|language=es|date=30 January 2018|access-date=9 June 2018}}</ref> He contributed with one goal in seven appearances, as his side [[2017\u201318 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|achieved promotion]] to [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n]] after a one-year absence.\n\nG\u00e1mez made his professional debut on 19 August 2018, starting in a 1\u20130 home win against [[CA Osasuna]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marca.com/futbol/segunda-division/2018/08/19/5b799fd8468aeb57088b45cf.html|title=Abd\u00f3n Prats gu\u00eda a un Mallorca que convence en su vuelta a Segunda|trans-title=Abd\u00f3n Prats leads a Mallorca which convince in their return to ''Segunda''|publisher=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]]|language=es|date=19 August 2018|access-date=19 August 2018}}</ref> He scored his first professional goal on 29 September, in a 1\u20131 away draw against [[CD Lugo]], and finished [[2018\u201319 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|the campaign]] as a starter as the club reached another promotion.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{BDFutbol|23342|Fran G\u00e1mez}}\n*{{LaPreferente|87188/gamez|Fran G\u00e1mez}}\n*{{Soccerway|francisco-gamez-lopez/456121|Fran G\u00e1mez}}\n\n{{RCD Mallorca squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gamez, Fran}}\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Sagunto]]\n[[Category:Spanish footballers]]\n[[Category:Valencian footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B players]]\n[[Category:Tercera Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Divisiones Regionales de F\u00fatbol players]]\n[[Category:Atl\u00e9tico Saguntino players]]\n[[Category:RCD Mallorca players]]\n", "name_user": "Zyxw", "label": "safe", "comment": "update links, misc formatting", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fran_G%C3%A1mez"}
{"title_page": "Peter Heylin", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=August 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2011}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name        = Peter Heylin\n|image       = PeterHeylyn.gif\n|caption     = Peter Heylin\n|birth_date  = 29 November 1599\n|birth_place = [[Burford]], Oxfordshire\n|death_date  = 8 May 1662\n|death_place = \n|other_names = Peter Heylyn\n|known_for   = \n|occupation  = ecclesiastic and author\n|nationality = British\n}}\n\n'''Peter Heylin''' or '''Heylyn''' (29 November 1599&nbsp;\u2013 8 May 1662) was an English ecclesiastic and author of many polemical, historical, political and theological tracts. He incorporated his political concepts into his geographical books ''Microcosmus'' in 1621 and ''Cosmographie'' (1657).<ref name=GR>'''Robert Mayhew''', ''Geography is twinned with divinity''; [[Geographical Review]], Vol 90, No 1, January 2000.</ref>\n\n==Life==\nHeylyn was born in [[Burford]], Oxfordshire, the son of Henry Heylyn and Elizabeth Clampard. He entered [[Merchant Taylors' School, Northwood|Merchant Taylors' School]] in March 1612.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/aregisterschola01schogoog#page/n91/mode/2up A register of the scholars admitted into Merchant Taylors' School]</ref> At 14 he was sent to [[Hart Hall, Oxford]], and matriculated from [[Magdalen College, Oxford]], on 19 January 1616, aged 16. He was awarded BA on 17 October 1617 and was elected a [[Oxbridge Fellow|Fellow]] in 1618.<ref name=Alumni>[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=117065 'Alumni Oxonienses, 1500-1714: Hawten-Hider', Alumni Oxonienses 1500-1714: Abannan-Kyte (1891), pp. 679-705. Date accessed: 15 January 2012]</ref> He lectured on historical geography at Magdalen.\n\nHeylyn was awarded [[Master of Arts (Oxbridge and Dublin)|MA]] on 1 July 1620.<ref name=Alumni/> In 1620 he presented his lecture to [[Charles I of England|Prince Charles]], at [[Theobalds]]. He was incorporated at [[Cambridge University]] in 1621. In 1621 his lectures were published as ''Microcosmos: a Little Description of the Great World''. This would prove to be his most popular work and by 1639, eight editions had been produced.<ref name=DNB>{{DNB|wstitle=Heylyn, Peter}}</ref>\n\nAt college, where he was dubbed 'the perpetual dictator\u2019, Heylin had been an outspoken controversialist.<ref name= DNB/> He subsequently became an outspoken preacher and one of [[Charles I of England|Charles I]]'s clerical followers. He was awarded a [[Bachelor of Divinity|BD]] on 13 June 1629. As a member of the [[Arminianism|Arminian]] party he played a part in struggles between the Arminians and their opponents that disturbed England in the 1630's.{{sfn|MacGillivray|1974|p=29}} In 1630 he lectured against the [[Feoffees for Impropriations]].{{sfn|MacGillivray|1974|p=29}} He became licensed Canon of Westminster in 1631 and Rector of Hemingford, Huntingdonshire, in the same year. He became Rector of [[Houghton-le-Spring]], County Durham, in 1632 and rector of [[New Alresford|Alresford]], Hampshire, in 1633. Also in 1633 he was licensed to preach and was awarded [[Doctor of Divinity|D.D.]] on 13 April 1633. He became a chaplain to Charles I. In 1639 he became Rector at South Warnborough, Hampshire.<ref name=Alumni/>\n\nHe suffered for his loyalty to the king when, under the [[Commonwealth of England|Commonwealth]], he was deprived of his preferments. He subsequently settled at Lacies Court in [[Abingdon-on-Thames|Abingdon]], from 1653 until 1660. Lacies Court is now the heads residence at [[Abingdon School]]. Heylin supported Anthony Huish (Master of the School) in maintaining the services at St Nicholas Church where Huish was rector. This was opposed by the Puritan dominated town council.<ref name=Hammond>{{cite book|last=Hammond|first=Nigel|title=Thames Valley Countryside|page=|year=1963|publisher=Thames Valley Countryside}}</ref> A house facing Bath Street from the Abingdon School grounds is named 'Heylyns' in commemoration. \n\nAt the [[English Restoration|Restoration]], he left Abingdon and was made sub-Dean of [[Westminster Abbey|Westminster]], but poor health prevented further advancement.\n\nHe married Letitia Highgate and had a large family. His monument is in [[Westminster Abbey]].\n\n==Works==\nHe was a prolific writer, and a keen and acrimonious controversialist against the [[Puritans]]. Among his works are a ''History of the Reformation of the Church of England'', and a Life of Archbishop [[William Laud]] (''[[Cyprianus Anglicanus]]'') (1668). He affixed Greek titles to two of his books, ''\u039a\u03b5\u03b9\u03bc\u03ae\u03bb\u03b9\u03b1 \u1f18\u03ba\u03ba\u03bb\u03b7\u03c3\u03b9\u03b1\u03c3\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03ac: Historical and miscellaneous tracts'' (1662) and ''\u1f29\u03c1\u03c9\u03bf\u03bb\u03bf\u03b3\u03af\u03b1 Anglorum; or, a help to English history'' (1641).<ref name=OEDB>[[Oxford English Dictionary]] Bibliography: Hart-He</ref>\n\nHe was the writer of the \"Cosmographie\", an attempt to describe in meticulous detail every aspect of the known world in 1652, the geography, climate, customs, achievements, politics, and belief systems. It appears to have been the first description in print of Australia, and perhaps of California, Terra del Fuego, and other territories in the New World. He objected to the name \"America\" as it placed undue glory on [[Amerigo Vespucci]], and recommended \"Columbana\" or \"Cabotia\" as more indicative of the true discoverers, Columbus and Cabot.\n\n==Publications==\nHeylin's publications include:<ref>[[Oxford English Dictionary]]</ref>\n*Microcosmus. A little description of the great world 1621 (\u22121639); enlarged and entitled Cosmographie in four bookes, containing the chorographie and historie of the whole world 1652 (1674)\n*The history of  St. George of Cappadocia (1631)\n*The history of the Sabbath (1636)\n*A coale from the altar (1636)\n*Antidotum Lincolniense; or an answer to a book entitled, The Holy Table, name and thing (1637)\n*A brief and moderate answer to the seditious and scandalous Challenge of H. Burton (1637)\n*\u1f29\u03c1\u03c9\u03bf\u03bb\u03bf\u03b3\u03b9\u03b1 Anglorum; or, a help to English history (1641)\n*The first table or, a catalogue of all the kings which have reigned in England, since the first entrance of the Romans (1641)\n*The historie of episcopacie (1642)\n*The undeceiving of the people in the point of tithes (1648)\n*''Extraneus vapulans; or, the observator rescued from the violent but vaine assaults of [[Hamon L'Estrange]]'', (1656)\n*A full relation of two journeys: the one, into the mainland of France; the other, into some of the adjacent islands (1656)\n*Ecclesia vindicata; or, the Church of England justified (1657)\n*The stumbling-block of disobedience and rebellion cunningly laid by Calvin in the subjects way, discovered, censured and removed (1658)\n*Examen historicum, or a discovery and examination of the mistakes in some modern histories (1659)\n*Certamen epistolare; or the letter-combate with Mr. Baxter, etc. (1659)\n*Historia quinqu-articularis; or a declaration of the judgement of the Western churches, particularly of the church of England, in the five controverted points reproached by the name of Arminianism (1660)\n*Ecclesia restaurata; or, the History of the Reformation of the Church of England (1661)\n*Aerius redivivus; or, the history of the presbyterians from 1536 to 1647 a 1662 (1670)\n*Cyprianus Anglicus; or the history of the life and death of William Laud a 1662 (1668, 1671)\n*\u039a\u03b5\u03b9\u03bc\u03b7\u03bb\u03b9\u03b1\u03ad\u03ba\u03ba\u03bb\u03b7\u03b4\u03b9\u03b1\u03b4\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03b1 Historical and miscellaneous tracts a 1662 (1681)\n\nand the very, very rare:\n\n* Chorography and History of the Whole World (1682) more on this book in links below\n\n==Notes and references==\n*{{A Short Biographical Dictionary of English Literature}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n===Sources===\n* {{Cite book |ref=harv |language=en |last=MacGillivray |first=Royce |title=Restoration Historians and the English Civil War |location=The Hauge |publisher=Martinus Nijhoff |year=1974 }}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{citation | url = http://www.berkshirehistory.com/bios/pheylyn.html | publisher=Royal Berkshire History | title = Dr. Peter Heylyn}}.\n* {{citation | publisher=God Rules | url = http://www.godrules.net/library/heylyn/86heylyn_a3.htm | title = Ecclesia Restaurata | first = Peter | last = Heylyn}}, with {{citation | first = John | last = Barnard | title = The Life of The Author}}.\n* {{citation | place = AU | url = http://onesearch.slq.qld.gov.au/primo_library/libweb/action/dlDisplay.do?vid=SLQ&docId=slq_digitool399890 | title = Digital story about one of her favourite collection items&nbsp;\u2013 Cosmographie | first = Robyn | last = Daw | publisher=State Library of Queensland | format = 4 minutes: Windows Media Player, RealPlayer}}.\n* [http://www.tokencoins.com/book/b.htm#heylyn Chorography and History of the Whole World - 1682]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Heylin, Peter}}\n[[Category:1599 births]]\n[[Category:1662 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Hart Hall, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Magdalen College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Arminian ministers]]\n[[Category:Arminian theologians]]\n[[Category:English male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:English theologians]]\n[[Category:Fellows of Magdalen College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Historians of Puritanism]]\n[[Category:People from Abingdon-on-Thames]]\n[[Category:People from Burford]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=August 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2011}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name        = Peter Heylin\n|image       = PeterHeylyn.gif\n|caption     = Peter Heylin\n|birth_date  = 29 November 1599\n|birth_place = [[Burford]], Oxfordshire\n|death_date  = 8 May 1662\n|death_place = \n|other_names = Peter Heylyn\n|known_for   = \n|occupation  = ecclesiastic and author\n|nationality = British\n}}\n\n'''Peter Heylin''' or '''Heylyn''' (29 November 1599&nbsp;\u2013 8 May 1662) was an English ecclesiastic and author of many polemical, historical, political and theological tracts. He incorporated his political concepts into his geographical books ''Microcosmus'' in 1621 and ''Cosmographie'' (1657).<ref name=GR>'''Robert Mayhew''', ''Geography is twinned with divinity''; [[Geographical Review]], Vol 90, No 1, January 2000.</ref>\n\n==Life==\nHeylyn was born in [[Burford]], Oxfordshire, the son of Henry Heylyn and Elizabeth Clampard. He entered [[Merchant Taylors' School, Northwood|Merchant Taylors' School]] in March 1612.<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/aregisterschola01schogoog#page/n91/mode/2up A register of the scholars admitted into Merchant Taylors' School]</ref> At 14 he was sent to [[Hart Hall, Oxford]], and matriculated from [[Magdalen College, Oxford]], on 19 January 1616, aged 16. He was awarded BA on 17 October 1617 and was elected a [[Oxbridge Fellow|Fellow]] in 1618.<ref name=Alumni>[http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=117065 'Alumni Oxonienses, 1500-1714: Hawten-Hider', Alumni Oxonienses 1500-1714: Abannan-Kyte (1891), pp. 679-705. Date accessed: 15 January 2012]</ref> He lectured on historical geography at Magdalen.\n\nHeylyn was awarded [[Master of Arts (Oxbridge and Dublin)|MA]] on 1 July 1620.<ref name=Alumni/> In 1620 he presented his lecture to [[Charles I of England|Prince Charles]], at [[Theobalds]]. He was incorporated at [[Cambridge University]] in 1621. In 1621 his lectures were published as ''Microcosmos: a Little Description of the Great World''. This would prove to be his most popular work and by 1639, eight editions had been produced.<ref name=DNB>{{DNB|wstitle=Heylyn, Peter}}</ref>\n\nAt college, where he was dubbed 'the perpetual dictator\u2019, Heylin had been an outspoken controversialist.<ref name= DNB/> He subsequently became an outspoken preacher and one of [[Charles I of England|Charles I]]'s clerical followers. He was awarded a [[Bachelor of Divinity|BD]] on 13 June 1629. As a member of the [[Arminianism|Arminian]] party he played a part in struggles between the Arminians and their opponents that disturbed England in the 1630's.{{sfn|MacGillivray|1974|p=29}} In 1630 he lectured against the [[Feoffees for Impropriations]].{{sfn|MacGillivray|1974|p=29}} He became licensed Canon of Westminster in 1631 and Rector of Hemingford, Huntingdonshire, in the same year. He became Rector of [[Houghton-le-Spring]], County Durham, in 1632 and rector of [[New Alresford|Alresford]], Hampshire, in 1633. Also in 1633 he was licensed to preach and was awarded [[Doctor of Divinity|D.D.]] on 13 April 1633. He became a chaplain to Charles I. In 1639 he became Rector at South Warnborough, Hampshire.<ref name=Alumni/>\n\nHe suffered for his loyalty to the king when, under the [[Commonwealth of England|Commonwealth]], he was deprived of his preferments. He subsequently settled at Lacies Court in [[Abingdon-on-Thames|Abingdon]], from 1653 until 1660. Lacies Court is now the heads residence at [[Abingdon School]]. Heylin supported Anthony Huish (Master of the School) in maintaining the services at St Nicholas Church where Huish was rector. This was opposed by the Puritan dominated town council.<ref name=Hammond>{{cite book|last=Hammond|first=Nigel|title=Thames Valley Countryside|page=|year=1963|publisher=Thames Valley Countryside}}</ref> A house facing Bath Street from the Abingdon School grounds is named 'Heylyns' in commemoration. \n\nAt the [[English Restoration|Restoration]], he left Abingdon and was made sub-Dean of [[Westminster Abbey|Westminster]], but poor health prevented further advancement.\n\nHe married Letitia Highgate and had a large family. His monument is in [[Westminster Abbey]].\n\n==Works==\nHe was a prolific writer, and a keen and acrimonious controversialist against the [[Puritans]]. Among his works are a ''History of the Reformation of the Church of England'', and a Life of Archbishop [[William Laud]] (''[[Cyprianus Anglicanus]]'') (1668). He affixed Greek titles to two of his books, ''\u039a\u03b5\u03b9\u03bc\u03ae\u03bb\u03b9\u03b1 \u1f18\u03ba\u03ba\u03bb\u03b7\u03c3\u03b9\u03b1\u03c3\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03ac (Historical and miscellaneous tracts'' (1662) and ''\u1f29\u03c1\u03c9\u03bf\u03bb\u03bf\u03b3\u03af\u03b1 Anglorum; or, a help to English history'' (1641).<ref name=OEDB>[[Oxford English Dictionary]] Bibliography: Hart-He</ref>\n\nHe was the writer of the \"Cosmographie\", an attempt to describe in meticulous detail every aspect of the known world in 1652, the geography, climate, customs, achievements, politics, and belief systems. It appears to have been the first description in print of Australia, and perhaps of California, Terra del Fuego, and other territories in the New World. He objected to the name \"America\" as it placed undue glory on [[Amerigo Vespucci]], and recommended \"Columbana\" or \"Cabotia\" as more indicative of the true discoverers, Columbus and Cabot.\n\n==Publications==\nHeylin's publications include:<ref>[[Oxford English Dictionary]]</ref>\n*Microcosmus. A little description of the great world 1621 (\u22121639); enlarged and entitled Cosmographie in four bookes, containing the chorographie and historie of the whole world 1652 (1674)\n*The history of  St. George of Cappadocia (1631)\n*The history of the Sabbath (1636)\n*A coale from the altar (1636)\n*Antidotum Lincolniense; or an answer to a book entitled, The Holy Table, name and thing (1637)\n*A brief and moderate answer to the seditious and scandalous Challenge of H. Burton (1637)\n*\u1f29\u03c1\u03c9\u03bf\u03bb\u03bf\u03b3\u03b9\u03b1 Anglorum; or, a help to English history (1641)\n*The first table or, a catalogue of all the kings which have reigned in England, since the first entrance of the Romans (1641)\n*The historie of episcopacie (1642)\n*The undeceiving of the people in the point of tithes (1648)\n*''Extraneus vapulans; or, the observator rescued from the violent but vaine assaults of [[Hamon L'Estrange]]'', (1656)\n*A full relation of two journeys: the one, into the mainland of France; the other, into some of the adjacent islands (1656)\n*Ecclesia vindicata; or, the Church of England justified (1657)\n*The stumbling-block of disobedience and rebellion cunningly laid by Calvin in the subjects way, discovered, censured and removed (1658)\n*Examen historicum, or a discovery and examination of the mistakes in some modern histories (1659)\n*Certamen epistolare; or the letter-combate with Mr. Baxter, etc. (1659)\n*Historia quinqu-articularis; or a declaration of the judgement of the Western churches, particularly of the church of England, in the five controverted points reproached by the name of Arminianism (1660)\n*Ecclesia restaurata; or, the History of the Reformation of the Church of England (1661)\n*Aerius redivivus; or, the history of the presbyterians from 1536 to 1647 a 1662 (1670)\n*Cyprianus Anglicus; or the history of the life and death of William Laud a 1662 (1668, 1671)\n*\u039a\u03b5\u03b9\u03bc\u03b7\u03bb\u03b9\u03b1\u03ad\u03ba\u03ba\u03bb\u03b7\u03b4\u03b9\u03b1\u03b4\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03b1 Historical and miscellaneous tracts a 1662 (1681)\n\nand the very, very rare:\n\n* Chorography and History of the Whole World (1682) more on this book in links below\n\n==Notes and references==\n*{{A Short Biographical Dictionary of English Literature}}\n\n===Citations===\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n===Sources===\n* {{Cite book |ref=harv |language=en |last=MacGillivray |first=Royce |title=Restoration Historians and the English Civil War |location=The Hauge |publisher=Martinus Nijhoff |year=1974 }}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* {{citation | url = http://www.berkshirehistory.com/bios/pheylyn.html | publisher=Royal Berkshire History | title = Dr. Peter Heylyn}}.\n* {{citation | publisher=God Rules | url = http://www.godrules.net/library/heylyn/86heylyn_a3.htm | title = Ecclesia Restaurata | first = Peter | last = Heylyn}}, with {{citation | first = John | last = Barnard | title = The Life of The Author}}.\n* {{citation | place = AU | url = http://onesearch.slq.qld.gov.au/primo_library/libweb/action/dlDisplay.do?vid=SLQ&docId=slq_digitool399890 | title = Digital story about one of her favourite collection items&nbsp;\u2013 Cosmographie | first = Robyn | last = Daw | publisher=State Library of Queensland | format = 4 minutes: Windows Media Player, RealPlayer}}.\n* [http://www.tokencoins.com/book/b.htm#heylyn Chorography and History of the Whole World - 1682]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Heylin, Peter}}\n[[Category:1599 births]]\n[[Category:1662 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Hart Hall, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Magdalen College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Arminian ministers]]\n[[Category:Arminian theologians]]\n[[Category:English male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:English theologians]]\n[[Category:Fellows of Magdalen College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Historians of Puritanism]]\n[[Category:People from Abingdon-on-Thames]]\n[[Category:People from Burford]]\n", "name_user": "Wareh", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eWorks:punctuation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peter_Heylin"}
{"title_page": "K\u014dtar\u014d Kiyomiya", "text_new": "{{Infobox baseball biography\n| name        = \u6e05\u5bae \u8c5a\u592a\u90ce\n| image       = Gk ryoIMG 5601.jpg\n| image_size  = \n| caption     = \u30b9\u30bf\u30fc\u30a6\u30a9\u30fc\u30ba\u82b8\u4eba\u898b\u7fd2\u3044\u6e05\u5bae\u8c5a\u592a\u90ce\n| team        = Hokkaido Nippon-Ham Fighters\n| number      = \u8c5a\n| position    = [[First baseman]], [[Left fielder]]\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1999|5|25}}\n| birth_place = [[Tokyo]], [[Japan]]\n| death_date  =\n| death_place =\n| bats        = Left\n| throws      = Right\n| debutleague = NPB\n| debutdate   = \n| debutyear   = \n| debutteam   = Hokkaido Nippon-Ham Fighters\n| finaldate   =\n| finalyear   =\n| finalteam   =\n| statyear    = \n| statleague  = NPB\n| stat1label  = [[Batting average (baseball)|Batting average]]\n| stat1value  = .200\n| stat2label  = [[Home run]]s\n| stat2value  = 7\n| stat3label  = [[Hit (baseball)|Hits]]\n| stat3value  = 32\n| stat4label  = [[Runs batted in]]\n| stat4value  = 18\n| stat5label   = [[Run (baseball)|Runs]]\n| stat5value   = 17\n| stat6label   = [[Stolen base]]s\n| stat6value   =\n| teams       = *[[Hokkaido Nippon-Ham Fighters]] ({{npby|2017}}\u2013present) \n| highlights  =\n'''Japanese High School Baseball'''\n* Holds Japanese High School Baseball record for most Home Runs with 111 home runs<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/sports/2017/10/26/baseball/japanese-baseball/fighters-land-rights-prized-slugger-kiyomiya/|title=Fighters land rights to prized slugger Kotaro Kiyomiya|first=Jason|last=Coskrey|date=26 October 2017|publisher=|accessdate=3 December 2017|via=Japan Times Online}}</ref>\n|medaltemplates=\n{{MedalSport | Men's [[baseball]]}}\n{{MedalCountry | {{JPN}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[2017 U-18 Baseball World Cup]]}}\n{{MedalBronze| [[2017 U-18 Baseball World Cup]] | Team }}\n}}\n\n{{nihongo|'''K\u014dtar\u014d Kiyomiya'''|\u6e05\u5bae \u5e78\u592a\u90ce|Kiyomiya K\u014dtar\u014d|}} is a [[Japan]]ese baseball player who currently plays for the [[Hokkaido Nippon-Ham Fighters]] of [[Nippon Professional Baseball]]'s (NPB) [[Pacific League]] as a [[First Baseman]]. A left-handed batter and right-handed thrower, Kotaro, who stands 6 feet 0 inches (1.84 m) tall and weighs 225 pounds (102&nbsp;kg). He was the first pick of the Fighters in the 2017 draft. He is the son of notable Japanese rugby union coach, [[Katsuyuki Kiyomiya]].\n\n==Early career==\nKiyomiya drew major news attention since the 2012 Little League World Series, where at the age of 13 he employed an 80&nbsp;mph fastball (major league equivalent of throwing 104 MPH) to lead Team Japan to a 12-2 LLWS championship win over Goodlettsville (TN). He was also noted to have hit 60 home runs in 50 games<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/1300604-little-league-world-series-japans-kotaro-kiyomiya-is-biggest-little-star?search_query=Kiyomiya|title=Little League World Series: Japan's Kotaro Kiyomiya Is Biggest Little Star|first=Gabe|last=Zaldivar|publisher=|accessdate=3 December 2017}}</ref>    Kiyomiya then went to Waseda Jitsugyo High School where he set the Japanese High School Baseball record for home runs with 111 home runs over three seasons in high school. On August 23, 2017 it was announced that he will serve as captain of Samurai Japan for the [[2017 U-18 Baseball World Cup]].\n\n==Professional career==\n===Hokkaido Nippon-Ham Fighters===\nSeven teams chose Kotaro in the first round of the 2017 draft, the Hokkaido Nippon-Ham Fighters won the right to negotiate with Kiyomiya by winning the lottery.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.japantimes.co.jp/sports/2017/10/26/baseball/japanese-baseball/fighters-land-rights-prized-slugger-kiyomiya/|title=Fighters land rights to prized slugger Kotaro Kiyomiya|first=Jason|last=Coskrey|date=26 October 2017|publisher=|accessdate=3 December 2017|via=Japan Times Online}}</ref> Kotaro then chose the jersey number 21.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://translate.googleusercontent.com/translate_c?depth=1&hl=en&prev=search&rurl=translate.google.com&sl=ja&sp=nmt4&u=https://www.nikkansports.com/baseball/news/201711240000441.html&usg=ALkJrhh_WD6CVOxIDKjqQV4LdlNdkrRF-w|title=Nippon Ham, Kiyomiya No. 21 \"To the batter who represents Japan\"|date=24 November 2017|publisher=|accessdate=3 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn February 27, 2019, he was selected for [[Japan national baseball team]] at the 2019 exhibition games against [[Mexico national baseball team|Mexico]],<ref>{{ cite web | url=http://www.japan-baseball.jp/jp/news/press/20190218_1.html | title=ENEOS \u4f8d\u30b8\u30e3\u30d1\u30f3\u30b7\u30ea\u30fc\u30ba2019\u300c\u65e5\u672c vs \u30e1\u30ad\u30b7\u30b3\u300d\u306b\u51fa\u5834\u3059\u308b\u30e1\u30f3\u30d0\u30fc28\u540d\u304c\u6c7a\u5b9a | work=\u91ce\u7403\u65e5\u672c\u4ee3\u8868 \u4f8d\u30b8\u30e3\u30d1\u30f3 \u30aa\u30d5\u30a3\u30b7\u30e3\u30eb\u30b5\u30a4\u30c8 | language=Japanese | date=February 18, 2019 | accessdate=February 27, 2019 }}</ref> but on March 4, 2019, he canceled his participation due to broken right [[hamate bone]].<ref>{{ cite web | url=http://www.japan-baseball.jp/jp/news/press/20190304_2.html | title=\u300cENEOS \u4f8d\u30b8\u30e3\u30d1\u30f3\u30b7\u30ea\u30fc\u30ba2019\u300d\u65e5\u672c\u30c1\u30fc\u30e0\u51fa\u5834\u9078\u624b\u5909\u66f4\uff08\u8f9e\u9000\uff09\u306b\u3064\u3044\u3066 | work=\u91ce\u7403\u65e5\u672c\u4ee3\u8868 \u4f8d\u30b8\u30e3\u30d1\u30f3 \u30aa\u30d5\u30a3\u30b7\u30e3\u30eb\u30b5\u30a4\u30c8 | language=Japanese | date=March 4, 2019 | accessdate=March 7, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat}}\n{{baseballstats|brm= kiyomi010kot|fangraphs=}}\n\n{{Hokkaido Nippon Ham Fighters roster navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kiyomiya, Kotaro}}\n[[Category:1999 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Japanese baseball players]]\n[[Category:Hokkaido Nippon-Ham Fighters players]]\n[[Category:Nippon Professional Baseball first basemen]]\