{"title_page": "Ganashakti", "text_new": "{{Use Indian English|date=December 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2015}}\n{{Infobox newspaper\n| name                = Ganashakti\n| logo                = Ganashakti Logo.png\n| logo_size           = 180px\n| image               = GanashaktiCover.jpg\n| image_size          = 240px     \n| caption             = \n| slogan              = \n| type                = Daily [[newspaper]]\n| format              = Broadsheet\n| foundation          = \n| ceased publication  = \n| price               = Rs. 3.50 Weekday Rs. 4.50 Weekends\n| owners              = [[Ganashakti Trust)]]\n| publisher           = Debashis Chakraborty\n| editor              = Debashis Chakraborty\n| chiefeditor         = \n| assoceditor         = Atanu Saha\n| staff               = \n| language            = [[Bengali language|Bengali]]\n| political           = [[Left]]\n| headquarters        = [[Kolkata]], India\n| oclc                = \n| ISSN                = \n| website             = {{url|ganashakti.com}}\n}}\n'''''Ganashakti Patrika''''' is an Indian [[Bengali language|Bengali]] daily newspaper published from [[Kolkata]], [[West Bengal]], [[India]]. Initially the paper started as an organ of the [[Communist Party of India (Marxist)]] West Bengal State Committee.<ref>[http://www.ganashakti.com/ Ganashakti] ''ganashakti.com''. Retrieved 30 December 2012</ref>  It first appeared as a fortnightly in 1967 and then it started as an evening daily for quite some time and finally converted  into a full-fledged daily newspaper. Presently Ganashakti has 3 editions in Kolkata, Durgapur and Siliguri having a daily circulation of 2,50,000.\n\nThe principal catalyst behind transformation of ''Ganashakti'' was [[Saroj Mukherjee]], a freedom fighter and CPI(M)'s state secretary during the 1980s. After Mukherjee's death his efforts were carried on by [[Anil Biswas (politician)|Anil Biswas]]. Ganashakti reached its highest circulation at the time of Biswas's editorship.\n\nThe present editor is Debashis Chakraborty.\n\nGANASHAKTI TRUST is the owner of the GANASHAKTI newspaper.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://ganashakti.com Official website]\n\n{{Newspapers in India}}\n{{CPI(M) publications}}\n\n[[Category:Newspapers published in Kolkata]]\n[[Category:Bengali-language newspapers published in India]]\n[[Category:Bengali-language newspapers]]\n[[Category:Communist newspapers]]\n[[Category:Communist Party of India (Marxist)]]\n[[Category:Publications established in 1967]]\n[[Category:Indian communist periodicals]]\n\n\n{{India-newspaper-stub}}\n{{CP-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use Indian English|date=December 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2015}}\n{{Infobox newspaper\n| name                = Ganashakti\n| logo                = Ganashakti Logo.png\n| logo_size           = 180px\n| image               = GanashaktiCover.jpg\n| image_size          = 240px     \n| caption             = \n| slogan              = \n| type                = Daily [[newspaper]]\n| format              = Broadsheet\n| foundation          = \n| ceased publication  = \n| price               = Rs. 3.50 Weekday Rs. 4.50 Weekends\n| owners              = [[Communist Party of India (Marxist)]], [[West Bengal]] State [[Committee]]\n| publisher           = Abheek Dutta\n| editor              = Abheek Dutta\n| chiefeditor         = \n| assoceditor         = \n| staff               = \n| language            = [[Bengali language|Bengali]]\n| political           = [[Far-Left]]\n| headquarters        = [[Kolkata]], India\n| oclc                = \n| ISSN                = \n| website             = {{url|ganashakti.com}}\n}}\n'''''Ganashakti Patrika''''' is an Indian [[Bengali language|Bengali]] daily newspaper published from [[Kolkata]], [[West Bengal]], [[India]]. The paper is an organ of the [[Communist Party of India (Marxist)]] West Bengal State Committee.<ref>[http://www.ganashakti.com/ Ganashakti] ''ganashakti.com''. Retrieved 30 December 2012</ref>  It first appeared as a fortnightly in 1967 and then it started as an evening daily for quite some time and finally converted  into a full-fledged daily newspaper. Presently Ganashakti has 3 editions in Kolkata, Durgapur and Siliguri having a daily circulation of 2,30,000.<ref name=\"Jaago Bangla to now take on Ganashakti daily\">{{cite news|title=Jaago Bangla to now take on Ganashakti daily|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2011-03-11/kolkata/28679951_1_cpm-leader-ganashakti-west-bengal-state-committee|accessdate=30 December 2012|newspaper=The Times of India|date=11 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe principal catalyst behind transformation of ''Ganashakti'' was [[Saroj Mukherjee]], a freedom fighter and CPI(M)'s state secretary during the 1980s. After Mukherjee's death his efforts were carried on by [[Anil Biswas (politician)|Anil Biswas]]. Ganashakti reached its highest circulation at the time of Biswas's editorship.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://ganashakti.com Official website]\n\n{{Newspapers in India}}\n{{CPI(M) publications}}\n\n[[Category:Newspapers published in Kolkata]]\n[[Category:Bengali-language newspapers published in India]]\n[[Category:Bengali-language newspapers]]\n[[Category:Communist newspapers]]\n[[Category:Communist Party of India (Marxist)]]\n[[Category:Publications established in 1967]]\n[[Category:Indian communist periodicals]]\n\n\n{{India-newspaper-stub}}\n{{CP-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Rangpuriya", "label": "safe", "comment": "Updated the editor's name.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ganashakti"}
